Beth,<br><br>
Sorry for the delay in getting back to you.<br><br>
You asked:<br><br>
&quot;Art, your explanation was very helpful. One question...after you've moved out of the distortion, do you ever get a clear, solid base to stand on or do the same areas continue to become distorted when your emotions kick in? Is there anything or type of response that is effective at kicking you out of it?&quot;<br><br>
With me, before I came to a self realization that I had PTSD and behavioral problems, nothing worked! As I became aware of things, I gave the keys to my head to a few trusted people who could snap me out of it if I got too bad. I really trained myself to respond positively.<br><br>
The other thing with me is that I had NO emotions. What people mistook for emotions was anger and rage and fear. Most of this stuff is fear based.<br><br>
There are classes and groups for wives of Vets with PTSD. I urge you to take advantage of these things. Check with your local VA hospital.  <br><br>
I also urge you to state your feelings on what you feel is unacceptable behavior, and stick to your guns.<br><br>
Art<br>
 
